Do you like dimsum? Do you like eating it in the morning? Then this is the place right here! Locally owned, the food is awesome, and just think of your waitresses as your Aunties. Love eating here!

Terrific dim sum. Locally owned business that deserves our support.  Their specialty is the lion's head fish ball on greens. Why lion's head?  It is a humongous juicy fish ball shaped like a lion's mane with savory sauce served on a perfectly crisp bed of greens.  Healthy and delicious.  You need to try this.  They also have some of the best dan tat or egg tarts around.  The owners a friendly and make you feel like one of the family.  Also tried any of their stir fried dishes especially noodles.  They have super high BTU woks in the back that literally look like a dragon breathing fire. Anyone who knows good Chinese food knows this is critical to properly prepared stir fry dishes.

The experience my fiance and I had here was very offputting. We left feeling disappointed and disrespected. We did not have a large order, however the staff forgot to bring our rice and neglected to bring the waters we had asked for. While dining, my fiance had to get our saucers and take out boxes. They made haste in tallying up our bill. The staff continued to stand over my shoulder as I counted my cash, then as I searched for my debit card and parking ticket. Upon return, the staff still hovered waiting to see the tip amount. I intended not to leave any tip, as my fiance provided all service besides bringing the food and processing my card. I was stopped by the staff immediately after standing. The staff member was calling me to turn around and shouted in a rude manner, "Hey, hey! You must leave a table tip!" I threw a single folded dollar on the table and proceeded to walk out. The staff member unfolded the bill, scowling at us as we exited the restaurant.

We came in a little before noon on a weekday. The place filled quickly, but emptied out by a little after 1 PM. Most patrons appeared to be locals or workers wanting a speedy in-and-out lunch. How they did so with the inattentive, haphazard service surprises me.  We were seated immediately, but after waiting almost 10 min for a server it took several attempts to flag one down (a male Cashier/? manager saw me gesture that we were ready to order, but ignored me). Couldn't wash up before eating because staff was not too busy to provide restroom (which was clean, but outside and about 30 yards away) key. Multiple requests were needed for a tea refill and water.  This is par for this type of place and is readily forgivable if the food is good. It wasn't. BBQ pork buns were cold; siu mai and har gow were lukewarm at best. And, STALE! With the exception of two non-menu items we requested specially, nothing we ordered appeared or tasted fresh. No wonder - most of the dim sum dishes were kept at a bare side table by the kitchen without even heat lamps or steam warmers.  To top it off, the check for four was nearly $60, not including the undeserved tip. I know things are more expensive here than on the Mainland, but I've had fine, fresh dim sum at many similar neighborhood places for $10-$12/person in San Francisco and NYC.  Overall, a major disappointment. I'd recommend giving it a miss.
